You are absolutely right. The native <details> and <summary> elements are significantly undervalued in modern web development. Because they are baked into the browser's engine, they provide a rock-solid foundation that remains functional even when your JavaScript bundles fail or are blocked—a "graceful degradation" that is hard to beat.

Nesting them—the "toast-in-a-toast" pattern—is where things get really interesting from an architectural perspective. It turns a static page into a multi-layered, interactive data structure without needing a massive state-management library like Redux or Pinia just to track which panels are open.

